</span><h2 id=the-benefits-of-having-a-good-website>The benefits of having a good website:</h2></div><ul><li><p>Allow members to join your organization and pay online.</p></li><li><p>Register attendees for events and accept online payments.</p></li><li><p>Collect donations online and automatically route that to your bank account.</p></li><li><p>Manage your database of volunteers, donors, staff, members and sponsors.</p></li><li><p>Generate automatic notifications and reminders for events and projects.</p></li></ul></div><div
class="block"><h2 id=advice-for-starting-a-nonprofit>Advice for Starting a Nonprofit:</h2></div><div
class="block"><blockquote><p>Examine your heart as to why you want to start your own nonprofit. Nonprofits are not the place for egos or attention seekers if you want to see powerful and authentic change in the lives of the people that you serve.</p><div
class="user"><div
class="user-wrap"><div
class="user-name">Heidi Stieglitz Ham</div><div
class="user-meta">
, CEO
at Spectrum Fusion</div></div></div></blockquote></div><div
class="block"><blockquote><p>Bring your impact audience into the development process of your organization. Encourage your funders to be as responsive and diligent as you are. And be patient with the practice of growing a company, instead of obsessed with the outcomes.</p><div
class="user"><div
class="user-wrap"><div
class="user-name">Nicole Cardoza</div><div
class="user-meta">
, Executive Director
at Yoga Foster</div></div></div></blockquote></div><div
class="block"><blockquote><p>Before anyone starts a nonprofit, they should spend at least one full year immersing themselves in the issue they are trying to solve. Get to know every player in the ecosystem: the clients, the funders, the colleagues and competition.</p><div
class="user"><div
class="user-wrap"><div
class="user-name">Gina LaMotte</div><div
class="user-meta">
, Founder
at EcoRise</div></div></div></blockquote></div><div
